notes: Identify the nuclei based on the DNA image. Objects are used for per-object QC measurements but this module and all subsequent modules (other than ExportToSpreadsheet) can be unchecked if you only want only whole-image QC measurements.

The settings here were chosen based on the image data and acqusition settings provided in Cimini et al., Nature Protocols, 2022. Changing the image acqusition settings may affect a number of these parameters. You should optimize these parameters until they perform well to identify nuclei in your particular dataset.
Typical diameter of objects: From the display window menu select Tools > Measure length. Click/drag to measure diameters of a few select nuclei.
Thresholding strategy: Global works fine in most cases but Adaptive may work better if the background has non-uniform illumination. However
the illumination correction in CorrectIlluminationApply should mitigate the latter.

Thresholding method: Select the method which provides the best foreground/background separation. Adjust the threshold corrrection factor if the threshold is consistently above/below where you want it to be for most images tested.
Lower threshold bound: Mouse over the background region to see the intensity variation in the lower-right of the display window.

Method to distinguish clumped objects: Use Intensity if the intensity gradient dividing touching nuclei are pretty clear even if clumpy. Use Shape if the nuclei are usually well-separated (and Intensity doesnt work).
Method to draw dividing lines between clumped objects: Intensity usually gives more realistic-looking boundary lines.
Size of smoothing filter/minimum distance between local maxima: Override defaults if nuclei are getting under/over-segmented.
